        <h2>Lecture 8: Variable Coefficient DEs and Intro to PDEs</h2>
        <hr>
        <h3>Cauchy-Euler Equation</h3>
        <p>This equation is transformed into a constant coefficient DE by using the substitution $$x=e^t$$. The operator transformations are:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>$$x\frac{dy}{dx} = Dy$$</li>
            <li>$$x^2\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} = D(D-1)y$$</li>
            <li>$$x^3\frac{d^3y}{dx^3} = D(D-1)(D-2)y$$, and so on.</li>
        </ul>
        <details>
            <summary>Example: Solve $$x^2\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} - x\frac{dy}{dx} + y = \log(x)$$</summary>
            <div class="solution">
                <p><strong>1. Substitute and Transform:</strong></p>
                <p>Using $$x=e^t$$, $$t=\log(x)$$, and the operator transformations, the equation becomes:</p>
                <p>$$[D(D-1)y] - [Dy] + y = t$$</p>
                <p>Simplifying gives $$(D^2 - 2D + 1)y = t$$, or $$(D-1)^2y = t$$.</p>
                
                <p><strong>2. Solve the Constant Coefficient Equation (in t):</strong></p>
                <p>The A.E. is $$(m-1)^2=0 \implies m=1,1$$. The complementary function is $$y_{cf} = (C_1 + C_2t)e^t$$.</p>
                <p>For the PI, $$y_{pi} = \frac{1}{(D-1)^2}t = (1-D)^{-2}t = (1+2D+\dots)t = t+2$$.</p>
                <p>The solution in terms of t is $$y = (C_1 + C_2t)e^t + t + 2$$.</p>

                <p><strong>3. Substitute Back to x:</strong></p>
                <p>Replace $$t$$ with $$\log(x)$$ and $$e^t$$ with $$x$$:</p>
                <p>$$y(x) = (C_1 + C_2\log(x))x + \log(x) + 2$$.</p>
            </div>
        </details>
