        <h3>Legendre's Linear Equation</h3>
        <p>This is a generalization of the Cauchy-Euler equation, with the form:</p>
        <div class="math-display">
            $$(ax+b)^n \frac{d^ny}{dx^n} + k_1 (ax+b)^{n-1} \frac{d^{n-1}y}{dx^{n-1}} + \dots + k_n y = Q(x)$$
        </div>
        <p>It is solved using the substitution <strong>$$ax+b = e^t$$</strong>. The operators transform as follows:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>$$(ax+b)\frac{dy}{dx} = aDy$$</li>
            <li>$$(ax+b)^2\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} = a^2D(D-1)y$$</li>
            <li>$$(ax+b)^n\frac{d^ny}{dx^n} = a^nD(D-1)\dots(D-n+1)y$$</li>
        </ul>
        <details>
            <summary>Example: Solve $$(1+x)^2\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} + (1+x)\frac{dy}{dx} + y = 2\sin(\log(1+x))$$</summary>
            <div class="solution">
                <p><strong>1. Transform:</strong> This is a Legendre equation with $$a=1, b=1$$. Let $$1+x = e^t$$. The DE becomes:</p>
                <p>$$[D(D-1)y] + [Dy] + y = 2\sin(t)$$</p>
                <p>This simplifies to $$(D^2+1)y = 2\sin(t)$$.</p>
                <p><strong>2. Solve in t:</strong> The A.E. $$m^2+1=0$$ gives $$m=\pm i$$. So, $$y_{cf} = C_1\cos(t) + C_2\sin(t)$$.</p>
                <p>The PI involves a case of failure since the operator $$D^2+1$$ annihilates $$\sin(t)$$. The PI is $$y_{pi} = -t\cos(t)$$.</p>
                <p><strong>3. Substitute back to x:</strong> The final solution is:</p>
                <p>$$y(x) = C_1\cos(\log(1+x)) + C_2\sin(\log(1+x)) - \log(1+x)\cos(\log(1+x))$$</p>
            </div>
        </details>
